            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "For Avi Cohen, the day begins not with an alarm, but with the scent of yeast. At 40, his life is intrinsically tied to the rhythm of his bakery, the one he lives directly above in San Francisco\u2019s Inner Richmond. His 0.0-mile commute is a simple walk down a flight of creaky wooden stairs into the warm, fragrant heart of his world.\n\nBorn and raised in the city, Avi is the son of Israeli immigrants who valued practicality over passion. His father, a taciturn plumber, couldn\u2019t understand Avi\u2019s disinterest in academics and his dreamy, unfocused nature in school. It was his mother\u2019s kitchen, filled with the smells of baking challah and rugelach, that provided his true education. While his report cards were mediocre, his hands learned the language of dough\u2014its texture, its needs, its potential.\n\nHis turning point came at sixteen. Floundering after high school, he took a job sweeping floors at a decades-old Italian bakery. The owner, a stern patriarch named Mr. Rossi, saw not a listless teen but a boy whose eyes lit up near the massive deck oven. He took Avi on as an apprentice, teaching him the science behind the sourdough starter and the art of a perfect croissant lamination. This was Avi's university, his entire career development forged in flour and fire. When Rossi retired ten years ago, he sold the bakery to his most dedicated student.\n\nAvi\u2019s life is his craft. He never married; a serious relationship in his late twenties crumbled under the weight of his pre-dawn hours and flour-dusted exhaustion. His social connections are now woven into the fabric of his neighborhood. He is the keeper of routines: the extra-dark sourdough loaf for the woman on corner, the morning bun for the commuting cyclist, the free cookie for any child with a scraped knee.\n\nHis aspirations are humble yet profound. He doesn\u2019t dream of a second location or franchising his name. Instead, he dreams of perfection: achieving the most open crumb in his ciabatta, sourcing a more flavorful local butter, and one day, finding a young, passionate apprentice to whom he can pass on Mr. Rossi's legacy. For Avi, the bakery is more than a business; it is his anchor, a warm, unchanging heart in an ever-evolving San Francisco."
